<TITLE> Bush urges Senate to confirm new military advisers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, June 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - President George W Bush on Thursday called for the US Senate to quickly confirm his choices for his top military advisers and warned that the risk of new attacks on the United States had not ceased. Passing up a fight for another term for his current chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, Gen. Peter Pace, because of his role in the Iraq war, Bush accepted the recommendation that Navy Adm. Mike Mullen be nominated to fill the position. Defense Secretary Robert Gates made the recommendation after concluding that Pace's role in the Iraq war would have led to overly contentious Senate confirmation hearings that focused on the past. "America's at war and we're at war with brutal enemies who've attacked our nation and who would pursue nuclear weapons, who would use their control over oil as economic blackmail and who intend to launch new attacks on our country," Bush said. Mullen said the way forward in Iraq and Afghanistan was not solely the military's responsibility. The Bush administration has spent months prodding Iraqis to solve their political differences as a way to end the unrelenting violence. "It cannot be a military path alone, that much is clear," Mullen said. Bush also nominated Marine Gen. James Cartwright to serve as vice chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, replacing Navy Adm. Edmund Giambastiani who said this month he planned to retire later this year. The two serve as the top military advisers to the president. Politicians and retired generals have blamed Pace and other top officers for failing to have a proper post-invasion plan for Iraq and using too few troops. More than 3,500 US troops and tens of thousands of Iraqis have died since US-led forces invaded Iraq in 2003 to topple Saddam Husse
